description.narrative: Output 4.2: Strengthened subnational capacity to implement and coordinate multi-sectoral scale-up of services to protect, promote and support optimal nutritional status of boys, girls and women, including in humanitarian situations., which contributes to Community-Based Management Of Acute Malnutrition, Infant And Young Child Feeding, Micronutrients, Nutrition And Hiv, Nutrition â€“ General, Prevention Of Stunting And Other Forms Of Malnutrition, Treatment Of Severe Acute Malnutrition. UNICEF aims to achieve this through Systems Strengthening And Institution Building. This contributes to the following Country Programme result: Outcome 4: Infants, young children and mothers have increased and equitable use of nutritional services and improved nutrition and care practices, with a focus on stunting.

description.narrative: Institutional support for the training of health workers on maternal, infant and young child nutrition and investment in commodity availability by UNICEF resulted in 90% of health facilities,against a target of 92%,offeringinfant and young child services and report of no stock out in 93% of facilities. These improvements together with the n community-based approach to stunting reduction and quality oversight by the centre of excellent for malnutrition management hasimproved nutrition care practices among86,586 mothers in18 district and increased early initiation of breastfeeding to 86% compared to 60% in 2021. | Status:On-track | As-of Date:11/01/2022
